I'll check your code asap (currently at work). Good job man :+1:

This is definitely strange.  Does it also happen if you download an [old stable release](https://az764295.vo.msecnd.net/stable/db71ac615ddf9f33b133ff2536f5d33a77d4774e/VSCodeSetup-stable.exe) and try to update it the same way?
There are no longer docs on how to setup the old alias. Do you still have that somewhere or should I go hunting in vscode-docs history?
``` vsc () { VSCODE_CWD="$PWD" open -n -b "com.microsoft.VSCode" --args $* ;} ```  Replace `VSCode` with `VSCodeAlpha` if using that one.
code () { VSCODE_CWD="$PWD" open -n-b "com.microsoft.VSCode" --args $\* ;} is the way it used to be on the VSCode setup page, I used vsc because I had another command aliased to code.

I have side-by-side installs of VS Code and VS Code Insiders. I opened VS Code that I already had installed and it needed an update. It was version 0.10.10 and it updated with no problems to 0.10.11 using the built-in process. I did not have to try your installer link that you posted. So what voodoo is going on here?
@bpasero any clues?

I realise that your are hitting these issues with the insiders build.  I wanna figure out whether you hit them as well with the stable. That's why I suggest to install an old stable build and wait for it to update.
How does that relate to VS Code? Sounds like a Windows 7 issue?
This issue was moved to OmniSharp/omnisharp-vscode#108

I uninstalled version 0.10.11 of the stable VS Code - not Insiders - from my system. I installed your download which is now version 0.10.8.   What do you mean "wait for it to update."? Will VS Code automatically update itself without having to press the "Update Now" button in the Info update message? If so, how long do I need to wait? Do I just press "Later" and then close VS Code?

@Cleod9 which module system are you using. Commonjs. In the past the tsc compiler was not correct in resolving modules in commonjs and they fixed this. In CommonJs there is no concept of a baseURL as in AMD. But the tsc compiler nevertheless walked up the parent chain. No if in commonjs and you want to reference another module you need to provide a relative path. It is the same as in JS with the require statement.

:+1: for @elgrego's suggestion on supporting pathogen. This kind of falls into the original suggestion from @giggio to support existing `~/.vimrc` files. In doing this, you could delegate the surround functionality to other community built vim plugins like https://github.com/tpope/vim-surround
You can press the button. :+1: Just do what you normally do when you get an update.

@bill-mybiz thanks for all your additional information. I tried to reproduce following your steps but wasn't able to do so. I will continue trying. The process explorer shows that the tsserver consumes quite some CPU so we know at least that there is something wrong with the server in our setup.  I am already on 1.8.9 which got released yesterday. If you have some time, could you give it a try on that version as well.
@raregrass there is a predefined problem matcher for this: $tsc-watch.   problemMatcher: '$tsc-watch'  That should help. Let me know if it works.

The file names are named using what architecture they're built as. For deb that is i386/amd64 and for rpm that is i386/x86_64, ia32 and x64 aren't valid architectures for deb/rpm files. It's best practice to keep these in the file names for clarity0. [I've been toying with the idea that we don't even need to provide the zip](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-website/issues/73#issuecomment-195578442) at all since deb and rpm files can just be extracted much like zips, only the package files contain addition files like the launcher which is becoming more and more essential. Reopen if there is still an issue.

@dbaeumer Yes we are using the commonjs setting in `tsconfig`. Note that we also use ES6-style imports for all TS modules.  Do you have a recommendation for what to change our tsconfig to? Webpack is able to build just fine because we're using its `modulesDirectories` config option, but there doesn't seem to be a way to reference extra modules folders besides `node_modules` in the current build for VS Code (although it seems it is planned for future iirc?)

@bpasero That makes sense -- so you would eventually plan on incorporating such features into the core product, but as a stop-gap measure, you want to use extensions, due to resource constraints. I understand, thanks.   I wish I could contribute code, but this isn't my area of expertise, so I'll have to contribute primarily through bug reports and feature requests. :white_check_mark:
Ok - the update had no issues. Stable went from version 0.10.8 to 0.10.11. Absolutely no issues...
Sorry for the late reply! I can't reproduce this with Node version 4.4. Closing the bug.

I used a WAMP server (http://www.wampserver.com/) to test PHP on Windows.  Verified built-in snippets and IntelliSense. Configured and tested linting with php.exe. Installed and tested debugging with XDebug extension.
I also think this is a feature sorely missing in an otherwise great editor.

I think this is due to running over Windows remote desktop.  I was able to get keyboard column selection to work on a Windows 7 machine when I was directly logged in.  I see the issue only when remoting to a VM (so far tried Windows 7 and 8).  I've update the issue title.  If this is only an issue through remote desktop, I think we can lower the priority

My particular case is using Internal Modules only, no imports and no commonjs modules. So unless there's something in my definitely typed ambient module definitions there's nothing related to module resolution. It's also specific to VSCode v0.10.10 because it works with the same version of typescript in the back-version of VSCode, but if your case helps to identify the conditions in which the VSCode Intellisense component stops taking input from the TypeScript language service I'm totally willing run diagnostics on test solutions on my project.
@egamma - TypeScript 1.8.9 is giving the same results as 1.8.2. ![typescript version](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5047398/13884975/3c90480c-ed28-11e5-9490-84a567fab506.PNG)

@AdamAndersonFalafelSoftware here is how to get the insiders build https://code.visualstudio.com/blogs/2016/02/01/introducing_insiders_build, but this one doesn't have 1.8.9 yet. To try out 1.8.9 you have to do the same as @LittleBrainz and use the tsdk option to use 1.8.9.  @LittleBrainz in this case I don't see how VS Code could be the culprit. Can you extract the good steps from https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/3842#issuecomment-197484962 and file an issue against TypeScript.

@AdamAndersonFalafelSoftware - TypeScript 1.8.9 is the current default on NPM. - Install TypeScript 1.8.9 globally with:  ``` sh npm install --global typescript ``` - On the File menu / Preferences / User Settings, edit the `settings.json` file to set `typescript.tsdk` to the folder path containing the tsserver and lib*.d.ts files to use. On my system I have:  ``` json "typescript.tsdk": "C:/Users/Stephen/AppData/Roaming/npm/node_modules/typescript/lib" ```  That should do it. But, be warned, the next version of VS Code may have a more up-to-date TypeScript, so you will have to comment out the line in User Settings when you upgrade next.

@joaomoreno how exactly was the windows build breaking in 3a3c9e15? Doesn't the `process.env['HOME']` only get evaluated if the task is called in to? It feels weird to do `process.env[(process.platform == 'win32') ? 'USERPROFILE' : 'HOME']` here when it should never be run on Windows.
@joaomoreno oh I think I got it; because we create the gulp task by calling `prepareRpmPackage`, I'll fix it up.
Thank you for filing. Dup of #3882. Will be fixed in the March release.

New versions of iTerm have changed the AppleScript API which broke the VSCode iTerm scripts. I made VS Code smarter in detecting what version of iTerm is installed and call either the old `iterm` or a new `itermNew` script.

This was intentional and follows the platform conventions (default to lowercase and no spaces). I would recommend not renaming the `code` executable but instead refreshing your symlink:  ``` bash SYMLINK_PATH="/usr/bin/code" # or where ever it is rm $SYMLINK_PATH ln -s /usr/local/lib/VSCode-linux-x64/code $SYMLINK_PATH ```  Also note that in the March release we will be offering a .deb package for easier installation which includes a desktop entry and a new and improved launcher bin command that accepts more command line args. You will want to remove your `code` symlink at that point. I'll make some notes in the release notes for the March release to help out users with symlinks set up.

Just found a clue to what may be causing it.  **codeEditorServiceImpl.ts**  ```     private static _getSelectorPrefixOf(theme:ThemeType): string {         if (theme === ThemeType.Light) {             return '.monaco-editor.vs';         }         return '.monaco-editor.vs-dark';     } ```  Changing the above `vs-dark` to `hc-black` (line 250) causes your icon to appear in the high-contrast theme.  This leads me to believe that we are treating hc-black theme as neither light or dark, so it's never getting your image.  I'm assigning to our development team to investigate.

@Tyriar Understood, but we could load `user\settings.json` exactly the same way we load `user\launch.json`, there is no need to use the settings store if we need to get at this value early in the boot sequence. The files sit next to each other on disk, they are both .json files, they can be loaded the same way.  The thing I am pushing for is a consistent user experience for settings. We have Preferences -> User and Workspace Settings already and this is where we put everything settings related. It is easy for people to learn.  I understand that the locale need to be global (User level) but we have other settings which are User only but exist in both user and workspace ("updateChannel" and "telemetry" are two examples). It is easy enough to understand that some things are User level and are ignored if found in the Workspace settings.  With us having a separate launch.json it creates more complexity. It is yet another file, it introduces another command in the command palette, it creates confusion because when i open settings I cannot find "locale" as an option (this is what got me started), and to follow our established model we would have to add another menu item under Preferences.  The only argument I can see for not putting the setting in user is that potentially, and I argue this is a only a remote possibility, the user level settings file could be so big that loading it to find the locale value would be a hit to startup performance. The size of a fully loaded settings file is 17k on disk (windows) and I'm guessing the OS could load that pretty fast :).  CC @egamma @dbaeumer

FWIW, coming from Vim and its infinite flexibility, I found VSCode's 3 vertical split limit vastly reduced cognitive load of splitting, switching and cleaning up. Where in Vim, I'd `<c-w>` ad naseum to get the 'perfect' set up for a particular coding problem and then not change it unless forced to, in VSCode, I found the `<c-\>`, `<c-1>` etc made for a much more fluid & adaptable layout, according to the particular context of what I'm working on. This, I think, is a hallmark of the ST/Atom/VSCode paradigm, simple fast & agile with reduced cognitive load.
